What I Learned

During this lab, I gained practical experience in identifying an SQL Injection vulnerability within a login feature.

The exercise reinforced several important cybersecurity concepts:

- Never trust user input.
- Authentication systems must validate and sanitize all incoming data.
- Parameterized (prepared) SQL queries are essential for preventing SQL Injection.
- Error messages can unintentionally reveal useful information to attackers.
- Security testing helps developers discover weaknesses before attackers do.

---

Defensive Recommendations

To protect applications against SQL Injection:

- Use parameterized/prepared SQL statements.
- Validate and sanitize all user input.
- Apply the principle of least privilege to database accounts.
- Avoid exposing detailed database or authentication errors.
- Implement secure authentication and logging practices.
- Perform regular penetration testing and code reviews.

